data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the EF Core Cosmos provider allowed you to suppress the sync-not-supported warning and use sync-over-async as an opt-in. **In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely.** All synchronous LINQ operators on the Cosmos provider now throw `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally.

Every call in your repository — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will fail at runtime.

### Fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

You can also remove the now-dead `ConfigureWarnings` suppression from your `DbContext` configuration — it no longer has any effect.

**Key callouts:**
- This cascades — every caller of these methods must also become `async`/`await` up the call stack.
- `Add()` remains synchronous (it's an in-memory operation, not a query).
- Relational providers (SQL Server, PostgreSQL, etc.) are **not** affected; this is Cosmos-specific.
